      Fake takeover
   =20
 =20
There is one main reason to do a fake takeover of a public company. You buy=
 some stock in the company. You announce a fake takeover: Put out a fake pr=
ess release saying the company has agreed to a merger, or put out a press r=
elease (or SEC filing) saying that you are doing a tender offer for the com=
pany at a premium. People read the fake announcement and think it=E2=80=99s=
 real, so the stock price goes up. You sell your stock before they notice i=
t=E2=80=99s fake. You slink away and hope you don=E2=80=99t get caught. (If=
 you get caught you  get in trouble.)That is the main reason to do a fake t=
akeover. There are=C2=A0others! Elon Musk  famously=C2=A0 did one=C2=A0on=
=C2=A0Tesla Inc. for no discernible=C2=A0reason; he was bored on Twitter, I=
 guess, and kind of annoyed that Tesla=E2=80=99s stock price was too low. H=
e  got in trouble for this, but not=C2=A0too=C2=A0much trouble, because he =
clearly=C2=A0wasn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0doing it for a quick fraudulent profit. Th=
e stock went up when Musk announced his fake takeover, but he didn=E2=80=99=
t sell. He wasn=E2=80=99t trying to trick people so he could make money.You=
 could imagine other possibilities. For a certain personality type it might=
 just be fun to do big-dollar=C2=A0mergers and acquisitions? I mean, to pre=
tend to? Like it=E2=80=99s a good role-playing game, being an Important Bus=
iness Person? You type up an adorable letter to the chief executive officer=
 of a big company saying =E2=80=9CDear CEO, I have lined up $11 billion of =
financing to acquire your company at $60.50 per share, what say you, the ga=
me is afoot,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and maybe you hear back from the CEO and negotia=
te a pretend deal, or maybe the CEO says =E2=80=9Cwho are you, what, no=E2=
=80=9D and you go public with a pretend hostile tender offer. Doesn=E2=80=
=99t that sound a little fun? I think if you are doing it for real =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0if you=C2=A0have the $11 billion and a good business case for acqu=
iring the company and actually plan to do it =E2=80=94=C2=A0it=C2=A0is=C2=
=A0kind of fun, though also intense and stressful. If you are just pretendi=
ng, maybe it is even more fun? You have a nice little negotiation and then =
you stop and do something else; you don=E2=80=99t have to worry about, like=
, marketing the debt financing or planning the integration or getting antit=
rust approvals.I don=E2=80=99t know. Here=E2=80=99s a truly wonderful U.S. =
Securities and Exchange Commission enforcement action against a guy named M=
elville ten Cate, accusing him of doing a fake tender offer for Textron Inc=
. in November 2020. The SEC does=C2=A0not=C2=A0allege that ten Cate did the=
 normal thing, buying Textron stock before his fake tender offer and then s=
elling it at a profit when it spiked. This does not mean he=C2=A0didn=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0do that; the SEC might just not have found the brokerage account =
where he did it. (Or maybe someone else traded and paid him for the fake te=
nder offer, etc.) But I prefer to think that he didn=E2=80=99t, that he did=
 it all for fun.For instance: The rational way to do this is to announce a =
tender offer, watch the price go up, and sell quickly. The=C2=A0public anno=
uncement is the way to make money, so you start with that. It doesn=E2=80=
=99t help you much to first approach the company with a private offer to bu=
y the company, because (1) you are not buying the company and (2) if you of=
fer to buy it privately, shareholders won=E2=80=99t know that, so the stock=
 won=E2=80=99t go up. It=E2=80=99s just a waste of time to try to negotiate=
 a fake deal privately.But in fact the SEC alleges that ten Cate pitched Te=
xtron on a deal long before his tender offer:On January 4, 2019, ten Cate, =
sole principal and self-identified Chief Technology Officer of Xcalibur, se=
nt an email to the Head of Investor Relations for Textron that included a l=
etter addressed to Textron=E2=80=99s CEO and a purported tender offer by Xc=
alibur to purchase Textron=E2=80=99s outstanding common stock for $66 per s=
hare. Textron requested documents to verify the legitimacy of the offer. In=
 response, ten Cate provided a number of documents to Textron concerning Xc=
alibur=E2=80=99s purported financial condition, including documents stating=
 that Xcalibur earned approximately =C2=A3161 million in revenue for 2018, =
and that in January 2019, Xcalibur had received a $6.4 billion investment f=
rom a member of the Saudi Royal family.=C2=A0All of this, says the SEC, was=
 fake: =E2=80=9CXcalibur had minimal, if any, operations and assets,=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9Cthe credit facilities and available cash referenced in the adv=
ertisement did not exist,=E2=80=9D etc. And so:Textron concluded that ten C=
ate and Xcalibur lacked credibility and could not feasibly have the financi=
al means to pursue the proposed offer. Accordingly, Textron=E2=80=99s CEO i=
nformed ten Cate via email that Textron was not interested in pursuing Xcal=
ibur=E2=80=99s offer.=C2=A0Undeterred, he tried again the next year, in=C2=
=A0February 2020, emailing the CEO =E2=80=9Cstating that he was authorized =
to =E2=80=98suggest a cash transaction at $60 per share=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D a=
nd providing adorably (allegedly) fake financial statements:Ten Cate provid=
ed Textron with Xcalibur=E2=80=99s purported 2019 financial statements, whi=
ch claimed that its revenue more than doubled to approximately =C2=A3360 mi=
llion and its assets increased to approximately =C2=A310.3 billion, includi=
ng approximately =C2=A39.8 billion in cash and cash equivalents. These 2019=
 financial statements were internally inconsistent. Among other things, alt=
hough Xcalibur claimed to grow from 238 employees at year-end 2018 to 414 e=
mployees at year-end 2019, its wage and salary expenses remained =C2=A36 mi=
llion and its operating costs were exactly =C2=A362,094,786 both years. Tex=
tron did not respond to the offer.Apparently frustrated by Textron=E2=80=99=
s failure to engage, ten Cate waited eight months and then =E2=80=9Carrange=
d for an advertisement to be placed in The New York Times announcing Xcalib=
ur=E2=80=99s tender offer for the common stock of Textron.=E2=80=9D The ad =
was published on Nov. 9, 2020. Textron=E2=80=99s stock went up =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0it got as high as $45.02 in morning trading, up about 15.9% from the pre=
vious day=E2=80=99s close =E2=80=94=C2=A0and then fell when Textron said it=
 was fake:Textron issued a press release responding to the purported tender=
 offer stating it=C2=A0belief that =E2=80=9Cthe purported tender offer is f=
ictitious and is being made in violation of U.S. securities laws, including=
 relevant filing and disclosure requirements.=E2=80=9D The release further =
stated that =E2=80=9Cin the past two years Textron has received other purpo=
rted indications of interest from Xcalibur, and each time Xcalibur has been=
 unable to provide details of its financial wherewithal=E2=80=9D and that =
=E2=80=9C[a]s it has done previously, Textron has informed relevant authori=
ties of this most recent fictitious offer.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Again, the normal,=
 fraud-y move here is to (1) sell stock first thing that morning, when it s=
pikes, and then (2) get out of town by the time Textron repudiates it. Ten =
Cate did not do that:Later that afternoon, ten Cate directed that a respons=
e to Textron=E2=80=99s press release be posted on Xcalibur=E2=80=99s websit=
e criticizing Textron=E2=80=99s senior management for not =E2=80=9Cengag[in=
g] in earnest=E2=80=9D and for =E2=80=9Cdiscarding [Xcalibur=E2=80=99s prev=
ious offer] out of hand, without consideration for their investors.=E2=80=
=9D According to Xcalibur=E2=80=99s statement, =E2=80=9C[t]he response of T=
extron [] does not surprise us, yet our offer stands and we will defend it =
in front of the SEC in the days to come.=E2=80=9DSee, that is what a real h=
ostile bidder would do. It does not seem like it would be very useful for a=
 pump-and-dump fake-tender-offer fraud, and the SEC alleges that he was=C2=
=A0not=C2=A0a real hostile bidder. But if you are going to pretend to be a =
hostile bidder, you might as well stay in character.There is so much other =
good stuff in the complaint. The SEC interviewed ten Cate and he stuck to h=
is story, telling them that =E2=80=9Cbillions of dollars in funds needed fo=
r the tender offer were held in escrow in a Swiss bank account,=E2=80=9D sw=
eet. Also the SEC alleges a hilarious pattern of stiffing service providers=
, like this guy who opened a bank account for him:Xcalibur U.S. existed sol=
ely on paper with no operations or assets. It was created in 2016 by a frie=
nd of ten Cate=E2=80=99s merely through the filing of paperwork in Delaware=
 and the opening of a bank account with a $100 deposit. After ten Cate fail=
ed to reimburse the $100, the individual withdrew the money and closed the =
account.And the state of Delaware:Further, at the time of the proposed tend=
er offer, Xcalibur U.S.=E2=80=99s corporate status in Delaware had been voi=
ded for failure to pay taxes.=C2=A0And the financial printer who prepared=
=C2=A0tender offer documents for him:In connection with the November 2020 a=
dvertisement and the phony tender offer, a New York-based printing and fili=
ng company hired by ten Cate provided technical services to Xcalibur in pre=
paration for filing the Schedule TO. Ten Cate never paid the company despit=
e providing multiple excuses for delayed payment and repeated promises that=
