<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Standstill</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A small lawyer point. Here is the <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27277787.256598/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTgwOTEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIyM=
Dk1NjUxL2QzNDIyNTdkZXgxMDEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB202dff5e" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
standstill agreement</a> that Elon Musk signed with Twitter on Monday. It h=
as three numbered paragraphs: (1) Musk will join the board, (2) he won=E2=
=80=99t go above 14.9% of the stock as long as he=E2=80=99s on the board (a=
nd for 90 days after he leaves), and (3) a tiny bit of legal boilerplate. I=
t=E2=80=99s great! This is the sort of thing that lawyers can do if they pu=
t their minds to it. If the richest person in the world is like =E2=80=9CI =
want to be on the board, in exchange I will agree to a standstill, and I do=
n=E2=80=99t want any other nonsense,=E2=80=9D then he will get this agreeme=
nt. And you can read it in like one minute and understand what it says.=C2=
=A0And=C2=A0<em>he=C2=A0</em>can read it in one minute and understand what =
it says and maybe even do it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27277787.256598/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTgwOTEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNT=
IwMDY3MzYyL2Q4NDY0MTVkZXgxMDIuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd47a8c05" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">standstill agreement</a> that Twitter signed with Elliott Management Cor=
p. in March 2020. It runs to 13 pages, plus a signature page, plus some exh=
ibits. It=E2=80=99s fine! It=E2=80=99s normal; this is what a standstill lo=
oks like. The first three pages basically say =E2=80=9CElliott will get a b=
oard seat,=E2=80=9D but in complicated ways. =E2=80=9CThe Parties acknowled=
ge that the Elliott Designee, upon appointment to the Board, will be govern=
ed by the same protections and obligations regarding confidentiality, confl=
icts of interest, related party transactions, fiduciary duties, codes of co=
nduct, trading and disclosure policies, expense reimbursement, director res=
ignation, and other governance guidelines and policies of the Company as ar=
e applicable to the independent directors of the Company generally, as they=
 may be modified from time to time (collectively, the =E2=80=98Company Poli=
cies=E2=80=99), and will have the same rights and benefits with respect to =
insurance, indemnification, compensation and reimbursement as are applicabl=
e to the independent directors of the Company generally, as they may be mod=
ified from time to time,=E2=80=9D says the Elliott agreement. Musk will jus=
t join=C2=A0the board. I guess they=E2=80=99ll give him the policies when h=
e gets there.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The next few pages say =
that Elliott won=E2=80=99t do bad stuff to undermine the company in shareho=
lder voting, etc., which I guess did not seem necessary with Musk. Page 8 i=
ncludes a clause saying that Elliott and Twitter will not =E2=80=9Cmake or =
cause to be made any statement or announcement (including any statement or =
announcement that can reasonably be expected to become public) that constit=
utes an ad hominem attack on, or that otherwise disparages, defames, slande=
rs, impugns or is reasonably likely to damage the reputation of=E2=80=9D ea=
ch other, though in vastly more words.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Musk=
=E2=80=99s agreement doesn=E2=80=99t say that because, you know, have you s=
een his Twitter feed? You are not going to reduce Elon Musk to calm docilit=
y by giving him a 13-page agreement to sign. Twitter=E2=80=99s worry here i=
s that if Musk doesn=E2=80=99t get his way in board meetings, he=E2=80=99ll=
 buy more stock and do a hostile takeover (or threaten to). That would be a=
 powerful and destabilizing tool for him, and Twitter wanted to neutralize =
it. They get one paragraph to make him promise not to do that. They picked =
their battles.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After that the Elliott agree=
ment contains=C2=A0the usual heroic amounts of boilerplate, including repre=
sentations from both sides that they have valid authority to sign the agree=
ment. Musk=E2=80=99s agreement doesn=E2=80=99t need that because it is sign=
ed by Elon Musk, who presumably has authority to sign agreements for himsel=
f, and Parag Agrawal, who is the chief executive officer of Twitter, and wh=
om Musk knows, and who Musk knows has authority to sign agreements for Twit=
ter. Stuff like that, stuff that has accreted through generations of carefu=
l lawyering but that sounds silly when you explain it to the richest and mo=
st distracted=C2=A0person in the world. =E2=80=9CWhy does he need to sign a=
n agreement saying he can sign the agreement,=E2=80=9D would be a fair ques=
tion.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically it is hard not to read Musk=
=E2=80=99s standstill and think =E2=80=9Ca better world is possible, for co=
rporate agreements,=E2=80=9D though I will tell you that it gives some lawy=
ers the heebie-jeebies.</p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0"=
 cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=3D"center">
