=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> got in trouble</a> for =
this, but not=C2=A0<em>too=C2=A0</em>much trouble, because he clearly=C2=A0=
<em>wasn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>doing it for a quick fraudulent profit. The st=
ock went up when Musk announced his fake takeover, but he didn=E2=80=99t se=
ll. He wasn=E2=80=99t trying to trick people so he could make money.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine other possibilities. For a cert=
ain personality type it might just be fun to do big-dollar=C2=A0mergers and=
 acquisitions? I mean, to pretend to? Like it=E2=80=99s a good role-playing=
 game, being an Important Business Person? You type up an adorable letter t=
o the chief executive officer of a big company saying =E2=80=9CDear CEO, I =
have lined up $11 billion of financing to acquire your company at $60.50 pe=
r share, what say you, the game is afoot,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and maybe you hear =
back from the CEO and negotiate a pretend deal, or maybe the CEO says =E2=
=80=9Cwho are you, what, no=E2=80=9D and you go public with a pretend hosti=
le tender offer. Doesn=E2=80=99t that sound a little fun? I think if you ar=
e doing it for real =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you=C2=A0have the $11 billion and a g=
ood business case for acquiring the company and actually plan to do it =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0it=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>kind of fun, though also intense and s=
tressful. If you are just pretending, maybe it is even more fun? You have a=
 nice little negotiation and then you stop and do something else; you don=
=E2=80=99t have to worry about, like, marketing the debt financing or plann=
ing the integration or getting antitrust approvals.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know. Here=E2=80=99s a truly wonderful U.S. Securi=
ties and Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/27277787.256598/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVh=
c2UvMjAyMi01OA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1611e789" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">enforcement actio=
n</a> against a guy named Melville ten Cate, accusing him of doing a fake t=
ender offer for Textron Inc. in November 2020. The SEC does=C2=A0<em>not=C2=
=A0</em>allege that ten Cate did the normal thing, buying Textron stock bef=
ore his fake tender offer and then selling it at a profit when it spiked. T=
his does not mean he=C2=A0<em>didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>do that; the SEC mig=
ht just not have found the brokerage account where he did it. (Or maybe som=
eone else traded and paid him for the fake tender offer, etc.) But I prefer=
 to think that he didn=E2=80=99t, that he did it all for fun.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For instance: The rational way to do this is to announ=
ce a tender offer, watch the price go up, and sell quickly. The=C2=A0<em>pu=
blic announcement </em>is the way to make money, so you start with that. It=
 doesn=E2=80=99t help you much to first approach the company with a private=
 offer to buy the company, because (1) you are not buying the company and (=
2) if you offer to buy it privately, shareholders won=E2=80=99t know that, =
so the stock won=E2=80=99t go up. It=E2=80=99s just a waste of time to try =
to negotiate a fake deal privately.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in =
fact <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27277787.2565=
98/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMi9jb21wLXBy=
MjAyMi01OC5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc7e072e1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the SEC alleges<=
/a> that ten Cate pitched Textron on a deal long before his tender offer:</=
p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On January 4, 2019, ten Cate, so=
le principal and self-identified Chief Technology Officer of Xcalibur, sent=
 an email to the Head of Investor Relations for Textron that included a let=
ter addressed to Textron=E2=80=99s CEO and a purported tender offer by Xcal=
ibur to purchase Textron=E2=80=99s outstanding common stock for $66 per sha=
re. Textron requested documents to verify the legitimacy of the offer. In r=
esponse, ten Cate provided a number of documents to Textron concerning Xcal=
ibur=E2=80=99s purported financial condition, including documents stating t=
hat Xcalibur earned approximately =C2=A3161 million in revenue for 2018, an=
d that in January 2019, Xcalibur had received a $6.4 billion investment fro=
m a member of the Saudi Royal family.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">All of this, says the SEC, was fake: =E2=80=9CXcalibur had mi=
nimal, if any, operations and assets,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cthe credit faciliti=
es and available cash referenced in the advertisement did not exist,=E2=80=
=9D etc. And so:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Textron conclu=
ded that ten Cate and Xcalibur lacked credibility and could not feasibly ha=
ve the financial means to pursue the proposed offer. Accordingly, Textron=
